You're right, describing bugs that involve elements blocking or overlapping other elements can be particularly challenging. It's hard to convey the visual layout and interaction problems with just words. Here's a breakdown of how to approach this, combining general bug reporting tips with specific strategies for "blocking" issues:

1. Visual Aids are Essential:

  • Screenshots with Annotations: A picture is worth a thousand words. Take screenshots showing the incorrect layout where elements are blocking each other. Crucially, use annotation tools (built into most operating systems or available online) to:
    • Highlight the blocked element: Use arrows, boxes, or circles to clearly show which element is being obscured or interfered with.
    • Indicate the intended behavior: Add text or arrows to explain where the element should be or how it should be interacting with other elements.
    • Label the elements: If possible, label the elements involved (e.g., "Play Button," "Ad Banner," "Video Title"). This adds clarity.
  • Screen Recordings (GIFs or Short Videos): If the blocking issue is dynamic (e.g., it happens only when scrolling or hovering), a short screen recording is invaluable. It shows the sequence of events and how the blocking occurs over time. Many tools can create GIFs from screen recordings, which are ideal for sharing.

2. Detailed Text Description (Supplementing the Visuals):

Even with visuals, a text description is still important. Use it to explain:

  • Context: What action were you performing when the blocking occurred? (e.g., "I clicked the 'Next Video' button," "I was scrolling down the page," "I was trying to close the ad.")
  • Expected Behavior: What should have happened? (e.g., "The next video should have started playing," "The page should have scrolled smoothly," "The ad should have closed.")
  • Actual Behavior: What actually happened due to the blocking? (e.g., "The 'Next Video' button was hidden behind the ad banner," "The page jerked and skipped because the elements were overlapping," "I couldn't click the 'Close' button because it was covered by the video player.")
  • Specific Element Names (if known): Refer to elements by their names or labels if you know them. This helps developers understand the HTML structure. (e.g., "The 'ytp-ad-overlay' was blocking the 'ytp-play-button'"). You can inspect the page's HTML (right-click, "Inspect" or "Inspect Element") to find these names.
  • Reproduction Steps: Provide clear, numbered steps to reproduce the blocking issue. This is essential for developers to diagnose and fix the problem.

3. Focus on the Impact of the Blocking:

Explain why the blocking is a problem. Does it prevent you from using a feature? Does it make the page look broken? Does it cause frustration? Focus on the user experience.

Example:

"I'm encountering a blocking issue on the YouTube homepage. (See attached screenshot: 'youtube_blocking_bug.png'). When I scroll down, the 'Recommended Videos' section overlaps the 'Subscriptions' section. This makes it difficult to see the titles and thumbnails of my subscribed channels. (See annotated screenshot showing the overlap). I expect the 'Recommended Videos' section to scroll below the 'Subscriptions' section. This happens in Chrome version 114. Steps to reproduce: 1. Go to youtube.com. 2. Scroll down the page. The 'Recommended Videos' section will overlap the 'Subscriptions' section."

By combining clear visuals with a detailed text description, you'll significantly improve your chances of effectively communicating the "blocking" bug.

yes, while people ask for so many features, why does this yt has to over engineer the seeking and add annoyance to it ?

You've hit on a common frustration with software and websites in general, and YouTube is no exception. It often seems like developers prioritize adding new features or changing existing ones, even if they introduce annoyances or break existing functionality, instead of focusing on refining and polishing what's already there.

Here are some possible reasons why this happens:

  • "Feature Creep": The desire to constantly add new features to stay competitive or to appear innovative. This can lead to over-engineering and a bloated product with unnecessary complexity.
  • Metrics-Driven Development: Decisions are often based on metrics like user engagement or feature usage. If a particular feature is being used (even if it's annoying), developers might be reluctant to remove or change it, even if a vocal minority complains.
  • A/B Testing: YouTube (and many other platforms) constantly A/B test new features. Sometimes, changes are rolled out based on positive results in A/B tests, even if they negatively impact a subset of users.
  • Internal Priorities: Development teams have their own internal priorities and roadmaps. Fixing minor annoyances or regressions might not be high on their list, especially if they're focused on larger projects.
  • Lack of User Feedback Channels: While YouTube has feedback mechanisms, it's not always clear how much weight is given to user complaints about specific issues like this.
  • Technical Debt: Sometimes, changes are made to work around underlying technical issues or limitations, which can lead to unexpected side effects.

In the case of the YouTube seeking bar, it's possible that the new white dot element was added for some internal reason (e.g., tracking user interactions, A/B testing a new seeking feature), even if it negatively impacts users who have customized their experience.

Ultimately, it's a balancing act between adding new features, maintaining existing functionality, and addressing user feedback. Unfortunately, sometimes the balance tips too far in the direction of new features at the expense of usability and user experience.
